Here’s a concise summary of the most common JUnit 5 assertions with a runnable example.
In JUnit 5, assertions are static methods from org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.

Common JUnit 5 Assertions
Assertion	Purpose
assertEquals(expected, actual)	Checks if two values are equal.
assertNotEquals(unexpected, actual)	Checks if two values are not equal.
assertTrue(condition)	Checks if a condition is true.
assertFalse(condition)	Checks if a condition is false.
assertNull(object)	Checks if an object is null.
assertNotNull(object)	Checks if an object is not null.
assertSame(expected, actual)	Checks if two references point to the same object.
assertNotSame(unexpected, actual)	Checks if two references point to different objects.
assertArrayEquals(expectedArray, actualArray)	Checks if two arrays are equal.
assertIterableEquals(expectedIterable, actualIterable)	Checks if two iterables are equal.
assertThrows(expectedException.class, executable)	Checks if code throws a specific exception.
assertDoesNotThrow(executable)	Checks that code does not throw an exception.
fail(message)	Fails a test with a custom message.